{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/how-many-pumpkins-do-you-need-to-cover-the-moon-f99a183e64aa", "time": 1683013837.060447, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/how-many-pumpkins-do-you-need-to-cover-the-moon-f99a183e64aa/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "How Many Pumpkins Do You Need to Cover the Moon? | by Arnoud Buzing | Towards Data Science", "h1": "How Many Pumpkins Do You Need to Cover the Moon?", "description": "Well, it\u2019s official. The first orange pumpkins have arrived in the grocery stores here in Central Illinois. That means it is officially OK to write a story about pumpkins, Halloween, and \u201cSpiced\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "http://the200acres.com/cucurbit-market/", "anchor_text": "The Great Pumpkin Patch", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://www.wolframalpha.com/", "anchor_text": "Wolfram|Alpha", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=surface+area+of+the+moon", "anchor_text": "surface area of the moon", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://blog.wolfram.com/2011/10/28/industrial-pumpkin-carving-with-mathematica/", "anchor_text": "very nice pumpkin carving blog post by Yu-Sung Chang", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "https://www.wolfram.com/language/", "anchor_text": "Wolfram Language", "paragraph_index": 4}, {"url": "https://reference.wolfram.com/language/ref/Quantity.html", "anchor_text": "Quantity", "paragraph_index": 4}], "all_paragraphs": ["Well, it\u2019s official. The first orange pumpkins have arrived in the grocery stores here in Central Illinois. That means it is officially OK to write a story about pumpkins, Halloween, and \u201cSpiced Lattes\u201d. Maybe not that last one. Illinois is the largest pumpkin producer in the United States, typically producing over 500,000,000 pounds of pumpkins. Most of those pumpkins, about 90\u201395%, are grown for food processing, and the remaining ones are grown for decorative purposes. A major \u201cU-Pick\u201d pumpkin farm, The Great Pumpkin Patch, is located near Arthur, Illinois.", "Pumpkins are inextricably linked to Halloween, a tradition introduced by Irish immigrants who originally carved jack-o\u2019-lanterns from turnips. The turnips were gradually replaced by the more available, and more easily carve-able pumpkins.", "Another special event is taking place on Halloween this year. The moon will be the Hunter\u2019s Moon, the first full moon after the Harvest Moon. I got curious about what it would take to cover the entire moon with pumpkins, so I did a little computation. The result is quite surprising and amazing!", "Let\u2019s start by asking Wolfram|Alpha for the surface area of the moon. This turns out to be 15,000,000 square miles. Quite a lot to cover. First, let\u2019s approximate our average round pumpkin as a cube where each side measures the diameter of the pumpkin. To generate the pumpkin shown below, I used Wolfram Language code from this very nice pumpkin carving blog post by Yu-Sung Chang:", "Let\u2019s assume we have a perfect pumpkin with a diameter of exactly 1 foot. That means its footprint, or pumpkin-print, is exactly 1 square foot. All we need to do now is divide the surface of the moon by 1 square foot. In the Wolfram Language we can do this using the Quantity function:", "So, we will need a little over 418 trillion pumpkins! One pumpkin with a diameter of one foot weighs between 12 and 18 pounds, so let\u2019s take an average weight of 15 pounds. The total weight (on Earth) will then be 6,272,640,000,000,000 pounds, or 6.2 quadrillion pounds. Given that Illinois produces only a paltry amount of 500,000,000 pounds of pumpkins per year, that means that is would take quite long to fully cover the moon:", "In other words, it would take 12,545,280 years for Illinois to grow enough pumpkins to cover the moon! There are ways to pack the round pumpkins closer together, for example by putting them in a hexagonal pattern, so that would take even longer.", "It\u2019s probably better and more fun to have a couple of pumpkins out by the front door for the next couple of million years. Happy Halloween!\ud83c\udf83\ud83c\udf83\ud83c\udf83", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "I create awesome software at Wolfram Research, makers of Mathematica, Wolfram|Alpha, Wolfram Cloud, and many other products and services."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Ff99a183e64aa&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fhow-many-pumpkins-do-you-need-to-cover-the-moon-f99a183e64aa&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fhow-many-pumpkins-do-you-need-to-cover-the-moon-f99a183e64aa&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fhow-many-pumpkins-do-you-need-to-cover-the-moon-f99a183e64aa&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=